Title:
Invoke Native Methods with DllImport (Boo Wiki)

Type:
Documentation

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This page shows how to call unmanaged/native functions from Boo code using .NET P/Invoke via `System.Runtime.InteropServices.DllImport`.  
- It provides small examples importing functions from `user32.dll` (e.g., `MessageBeep`, `MessageBox`) and `msvcrt.dll` (e.g., `puts`, `_flushall`).  
- It demonstrates basic DllImport usage, including specifying an `EntryPoint` to map a Boo function name to a different exported symbol name.  
- The page briefly notes a more cross-platform alternative for beeping (`Microsoft.VisualBasic.Interaction.Beep`) that works on both .NET and Mono.  
- Useful for developers, red teamers, and tool authors who need direct access to Win32/CRT APIs from Boo without writing a separate native wrapper.

Technical Focus:
- .NET P/Invoke (`DllImportAttribute`)
- Interop with unmanaged DLL exports (Win32, MSVCRT)
- Function signature mapping and marshaling basics (strings/ints)
- `EntryPoint` name binding for imported functions
- Boo language interop with .NET/Mono runtime

Use Cases:
- Calling Win32 UI functions (MessageBox/MessageBeep) from Boo utilities
- Invoking C runtime functions for quick console output/testing
- Building Boo-based tooling that needs direct Windows API access
- Prototyping interop signatures before implementing in other .NET languages

Keywords:
Boo, .NET, Mono, P/Invoke, DllImport, System.Runtime.InteropServices, user32.dll, msvcrt.dll, MessageBeep, MessageBox, puts, _flushall, EntryPoint, unmanaged code, native API, interop, marshaling